🧠 Topic: Emergency Provisions in India

(Extremely important for UPSC Prelims + Mains GS-II.)

1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What are Emergency Provisions?

Emergency provisions allow the Central Government to assume extraordinary powers during crisis.

📌 Borrowed from Germany (Weimar Constitution)

Emergency provisions are in:

Article 352 → National Emergency
Article 356 → President’s Rule (State Emergency)
Article 360 → Financial Emergency
🔵 1️⃣ National Emergency (Article 352)

Can be proclaimed on grounds of:

War
External Aggression
Armed Rebellion

📌 Earlier “internal disturbance”; replaced by armed rebellion by 44th Amendment.

Effects:
Centre becomes very powerful
Federal structure becomes unitary-like
Some Fundamental Rights may be affected
🔴 Approval

Must be approved by Parliament within 1 month.

2️⃣ State Emergency / President’s Rule (Article 356)

Imposed when:

👉 Constitutional machinery fails in a state.

Examples:

No majority government
Breakdown of governance

Effects:

State government dismissed
Parliament exercises state legislative powers

📌 Very frequently asked.

3️⃣ Financial Emergency (Article 360)

Declared if financial stability is threatened.

Effects may include:

Reduction of salaries
Centre directions to states

📌 Never imposed in India till now.

🔹 Important Safeguards
44th Amendment (1978)

Added protections against misuse:

Written advice of Cabinet needed
Approval stricter
Protection of rights improved
🔹 Important Facts
Emergency	Article
National Emergency	352
President’s Rule	356
Financial Emergency	360
